    content: "The transition from residential treatment to independent living is the most dangerous period in early recovery — and the most underestimated. Understanding how to navigate it can make the difference between sustained sobriety and relapse.\n\n## Why the Transition Is So Risky\n\nRehab is a controlled environment. Discharge day sends you back to the real world — and for many people, back to the same environment that contributed to their addiction. Research shows the first 90 days after leaving residential treatment are the highest-risk period for relapse.\n\n## What Sober Living Provides\n\nSober living bridges the gap between the complete structure of residential treatment and the full independence of returning home. You work, pay rent, and live in the real world — with community and accountability around you.\n\n## Start Looking Before You Leave Treatment\n\nBegin researching sober living homes at least two to three weeks before your discharge date. Call multiple homes. Ask about management, drug testing, employment requirements, and what happens when a resident relapses.\n\n## Your First Week\n\nExpect an adjustment. Meet your housemates, review house rules, start your job search if you're not already employed, and get into a routine. At Ocean Breeze, live-in manager Kevin Smith is on-site to welcome you and answer questions personally.\n\n## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\nIsolating in your room. Not getting a sponsor quickly. Delaying job search. Returning to old social circles. Not communicating with your house manager when things get hard.\n\n## How Long to Stay\n\nResearch consistently supports longer stays. Plan for a minimum of 90 days and reassess from there. Ocean Breeze has no maximum stay — residents leave when they're genuinely ready.\n\nCall Kevin at (561) 646-7097 to discuss your situation and check availability.",
