    content: "Do sober living homes drug test? At any serious, accountable sober living home — yes. And that's a feature, not a bug.\n\n## Not All Homes Drug Test\n\nSome homes operate on an honor system with minimal testing and enforcement. These feel less restrictive, but they're only as strong as the most vulnerable resident. If one person is using and the house doesn't know, the entire recovery environment is compromised.\n\n## Types of Tests Used\n\nMost homes use urine drug screens (UDS) that detect amphetamines, cocaine, THC, opiates, oxycodone, benzodiazepines, buprenorphine, fentanyl, and alcohol. Breathalyzers are sometimes used for alcohol. Disclose any prescribed medications before your first test.\n\n## How Random Testing Works\n\nTrue random testing means no advance notice — any day, any time, any frequency. This is intentional: a motivated person can time use around predictable tests. At Ocean Breeze, Kevin Smith administers tests without a predictable pattern.\n\n## What Happens If You Test Positive\n\nAt Ocean Breeze: zero tolerance. A positive test means discharge. This protects the resident (who now needs a higher level of care) and every other resident whose recovery environment is directly affected by active use in the home.\n\n## Why Testing Actually Helps\n\nExternal accountability reduces the decision you have to make in a moment of weakness. It protects the community you depend on. It builds genuine self-trust over time through a track record of clean tests.\n\nCall (561) 646-7097 to ask about Ocean Breeze's drug testing policy.",
