    content: "Men and women experience recovery differently. The challenges, social dynamics, and recovery approaches that work best aren't always the same across genders. That's why men's-only sober living homes exist — and why many men do better in them.\n\n## Why Men's-Only Sober Living?\n\nGender-specific sober living creates an environment where residents can be more open, more vulnerable, and more accountable without the social dynamics that mixed-gender settings can create. Peer relationships are often stronger, and conversations about recovery can go deeper.\n\nResearch in addiction treatment consistently shows that gender-responsive programming — treatment and housing designed with the specific experiences of men or women in mind — leads to better outcomes.\n\n## What to Look For in Men's Sober Living in Palm Beach County\n\n**Live-in male management**: A live-in manager who is himself in recovery provides credibility, mentorship, and accountability that a staff employee simply can't replicate.\n\n**Clear employment expectations**: Men in recovery need purpose and financial structure. The best men's homes require employment or active job searching from day one.\n\n**Small and community-oriented**: The best recovery happens in real relationships. A small men's home — 8 to 12 residents — creates community instead of just cohabitation.\n\n**Structured but not institutional**: Men do well with clear expectations. But an overly rigid, institution-like environment can feel dehumanizing. Look for homes that have structure with dignity.\n\n**Drug testing**: Random drug screening protects the entire community. If a home doesn't drug test, consider that a red flag.\n\n## Palm Beach County Recovery Housing Overview\n\nPalm Beach County has a well-established recovery community. West Palm Beach in particular is home to numerous outpatient programs, AA and NA meetings, sober recreational activities, and employment opportunities suited to men in early recovery.\n\n## Ocean Breeze Recovery Housing\n\nOcean Breeze is a men's-only sober living home in West Palm Beach, FL. Our 8-bed home is managed by Kevin Smith, a live-in manager who is himself in long-term recovery. $275/week, all-inclusive. Employment required. Drug screening in place. Pursuing FARR certification.\n\nCall (561) 646-7097 or apply online to check availability.",
